A good trade is, you go to a bank and ask to borrow a billion dollars, and =
the bank gives you the billion dollars, and then the bank comes to you and =
says =E2=80=9Chey I just made this billion-dollar loan to you, do you want =
to buy it,=E2=80=9D and you say =E2=80=9Csure I=E2=80=99ll pay you $836 mil=
lion for it,=E2=80=9D and the bank says =E2=80=9Cugh fine I guess.=E2=80=9D=
 And now you have borrowed $1 billion and paid back $836 million and made a=
 $164 million profit all at once.   Here you go:

Elliott Investment Management bought about $1 billion of the junk-bond deal=
 supporting its own buyout of software company Citrix Systems Inc., accordi=
ng to people with knowledge of the matter.
The Paul Singer run firm was enticed by the steep discount the banks that u=
nderwrote and distributed the Citrix financing commitment offered on the de=
bt, said the people, who asked not to be named discussing a private transac=
tion. The 6.5% secured bonds priced at 83.6 cents on the dollar Tuesday, br=
inging the all-in yield on the debt to around 10%. =E2=80=A6
The decision helped support a transaction that banks struggled to sell to i=
nvestors for months. Wall Street banks underwrote a $15 billion debt packag=
e in January to fund Vista Equity Partners and Elliott=E2=80=99s buyout of =
Citrix. Since then, credit conditions have worsened and borrowing costs hav=
e spiked, forcing the banks to absorb steep losses to offload the risk, and=
 also sweeten the covenant package.=C2=A0
Firms led by Credit Suisse Group AG lost more than $500 million on the secu=
red bond portion alone, Bloomberg reported.

I mean it=E2=80=99s not=C2=A0that=C2=A0good a trade. The reason Elliott and=
 Vista are borrowing $15 billion is to  buy Citrix for about $17 billion in=
 a deal they  signed in January and expect to close at  the end of this mon=
th. Before they signed,=C2=A0Citrix stock was trading in the $80s, and they=
 agreed to pay $104, a premium over the trading price. After they signed, t=
he stock market crashed, interest rates went up, and the shares of comparab=
le software companies are down 20% to 45%. Elliott is probably not thrilled=
 about owning Citrix at $104 per share, even if it got back $164 million on=
 the loan. (Plus, presumably the pocket of Elliott that is making the loan =
is different from the pocket of Elliott that is receiving it.) Still if you=
 can lend money to yourself and have some banks throw in some extra money f=
or free, that=E2=80=99s good.
The basic story of leveraged buyout debt is: In a bull market, every week s=
ome private equity firm signs an agreement to do an LBO of some big public =
company. These deals have financing commitments from banks, where the banks=
 promise to lend the buyer the money to buy the company at some maximum int=
erest rate. But the deal won=E2=80=99t close for several months while the c=
ompany gets shareholder and regulatory approval, and the banks don=E2=80=99=
t actually raise the money =E2=80=94=C2=A0selling bonds and loans to invest=
ors to fund their financing commitment =E2=80=94=C2=A0until shortly before =
closing. And so every week of the bull market banks are making lots of lend=
ing commitments at bull-market rates. And then one day the market turns, in=
terest rates go up, and all the loans that banks agreed to make at last wee=
k=E2=80=99s rates turn out to be mispriced this week. And then months later=
 they actually go and sell those bonds and loans, in a bear market, at the =
interest rates they agreed to in their bull-market commitment letters. And =
they get, you know, 83.6 cents on the dollar.
And they look kind of bad, but that is the nature of a cyclical business wh=
ere you hold inventory for months. You could do some hedging, both of inter=
est rates and of broad high-yield credit.=C2=A0But ultimately if you are an=
 investment bank you are in a competitive business of servicing private equ=
ity firms, and if one of those firms is negotiating a huge leveraged buyout=
 it is generally good for your career to be a part of it. (Also the fees ar=
e=C2=A0good.) =E2=80=9CNo, we=E2=80=99ll sit this loan out because we worry=
 the market will turn in a few months=E2=80=9D is a tough position to take.
  [1]
=C2=A0=E2=80=9CAs long as the music is playing, you=E2=80=99ve got to get u=
p and dance,=E2=80=9D Citigroup Inc. Chief Executive Officer Chuck Prince f=
amously said in 2007,  about the LBO lending business, just before the musi=
c stopped.
Anyway now everyone=E2=80=99s very unhappy about Citrix, which looks like t=
he turning point in the latest leveraged buyout cycle. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s =
  Davide Scigliuzzo writes:

Banks are nursing more than $600 million of losses on bonds and loans they =
just sold to investors at a steep discount. And they=E2=80=99re sitting on =
about $6.5 billion more Citrix debt that they=E2=80=99ll be stuck with inde=
finitely.
It may be just the beginning. After the biggest private-equity buyout boom =
in more than a decade, bankers still have to offload more than $50 billion =
in risky financing commitments, according to Deutsche Bank AG estimates. Wi=
th central banks hiking interest rates to fight inflation and recession ang=
st intensifying, few investors want to touch the debt without massive disco=
unts, leaving the assets deeply underwater.
Major banks have already taken roughly $2 billion of writedowns this year. =
But those are now crystallizing into actual losses. The usually lucrative l=
everaged-finance business has all but dried up. Bonuses are being slashed. =
Job cuts may be next. =E2=80=A6
There are other big financings in the market. Banks are trying to sell abou=
t $3.9 billion of debt for Apollo Global Management Inc.=E2=80=99s acquisit=
ion of some internet assets from Lumen Technologies Inc. And two more deals=
 are ahead: $8.35 billion of bonds and loans for the buyout of TV ratings c=
ompany Nielsen Holdings by Elliott Investment Management and Brookfield Ass=
et Management, and $5.4 billion for auto parts firm Tenneco Inc.=E2=80=99s =
buyout by Apollo.

I can think of one more! Roughly a quarter of the $50 billion of risky fina=
ncing commitments that banks still have to sell is the  $13 billion financi=
ng package for Elon Musk=E2=80=99s buyout of Twitter Inc., which was agreed=
 in April, when the market was much better and when Musk  had plans to make=
 Twitter profitable. Those loans don=E2=80=99t look so good=C2=A0now that r=
ates are higher, the market is weaker and Musk is   going around saying tha=
t Twitter is a fraud that =E2=80=9Cthreaten[s] U.S. national security and d=
emocracy itself.=E2=80=9D If that financing prices at 85 cents on the dolla=
r =E2=80=94=C2=A0comparable to Citrix, whose buyers=C2=A0don=E2=80=99t=C2=
=A0think it=E2=80=99s a huge fraud
  [2]
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0then that=E2=80=99s another $2 billion of losses for the ba=
nks right there.=C2=A0
Of course Elon Musk has told Twitter repeatedly that he=E2=80=99s terminati=
ng that deal, and if he doesn=E2=80=99t actually buy Twitter then the banks=
 don=E2=80=99t have to fund those loans. Twitter has sued to force Musk to =
close, and I think the market views it as more likely than not, though by n=
o means certain, that Twitter will win. If you are Morgan Stanley =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0Musk=E2=80=99s lead bank, on the hook for about 27% of the financing =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0how do you=C2=A0account=C2=A0for that commitment? Like when =
your quarter ends next week, do you take a $500 million writedown because y=
ou have a big debt commitment that is underwater? Or do you say =E2=80=9Coh=
 no this deal is canceled, no more commitment until we hear otherwise from =
a judge=E2=80=9D? Do you probability-weight it? If you are Musk=E2=80=99s c=
overage banker, and you take a non-zero writedown, what is that conversatio=
n with Musk like? =E2=80=9CSorry yeah our accountants forced us to recogniz=
e that you=E2=80=99re going to lose=E2=80=9D?=C2=A0
Elsewhere here is the Wall Street Journal on  Citrix as a bad omen for LBOs=
:

The difficulties in executing Citrix=E2=80=99s debt deal will likely make b=
anks even more reluctant to underwrite large LBOs, investors said.
=E2=80=9CBanks are in the moving business, not the storage business,=E2=80=
=9D said Steven Hunter, chief executive at 9fin, a credit analytics platfor=
m. =E2=80=9CThey need to clear these deals in order to give them the capaci=
ty to underwrite new transactions.=E2=80=9D

If you=E2=80=99re in the moving business and it takes months to move, then =
you are also a little bit in the storage business. If you keep buying inven=
tory as the market goes up, you will lose money on your inventory when the =
market goes down.
  [3]
=C2=A0And probably stop buying so much inventory.=C2=A0
And here is  the Financial Times on Citrix:

A hedge fund portfolio manager who reported being approached by Credit Suis=
se on the secured bond was surprised to hear from the lender.
=E2=80=9CIf they=E2=80=99re calling us to find out what terms we would do o=
n the secured bond deal, they=E2=80=99ve really gone down the list,=E2=80=
=9D the manager said, pointing out that the fund does not typically operate=
 in the high-yield credit space.

Might as well try everyone. Maybe the people who are not high-yield investo=
rs won=E2=80=99t notice that the high-yield market has turned.

