Does   this work?

JPMorgan Chase and Co. executives were in a bind. Amid a flurry of job-hopp=
ing on Wall Street last year, Chief Executive Officer Jamie Dimon had told =
the bank=E2=80=99s US staff it was time to return to offices on a regular b=
asis. But with Covid-19 cases climbing at the time, some managers were relu=
ctant to take a hard line with staff who could quit. A number of divisions =
were already wrestling with resignations and racing to refill positions.
So an informal strategy emerged to shield the rank and file from the CEO=E2=
=80=99s dictate without antagonizing him, according to people with direct k=
nowledge of the matter, who asked not to be named discussing internal pract=
ices.
Anyone who Dimon might possibly walk the halls looking for, such as a manag=
ing director, needed to come into the office. They just couldn=E2=80=99t ta=
ke the risk. Many others, though, were given leeway to keep working from ho=
me discreetly. The recruiters were busy enough. (Joe Evangelisti, a spokesm=
an for the bank, says assertions that such a system existed are =E2=80=9Cfa=
lse.=E2=80=9D)

Well sure fine sometimes Jamie Dimon=C2=A0walks the halls because he is loo=
king for specific people; he wants to grill some MD about a transaction and=
 woe to her if he can=E2=80=99t find her. But=C2=A0as he walks=C2=A0=E2=80=
=94=C2=A0to find that MD, or to go to lunch or whatever =E2=80=94=C2=A0he c=
an look around, and if it=E2=80=99s a ghost town he might notice. Like if h=
e walks onto the trading floor to grill an MD about a trade and=C2=A0she=E2=
=80=99s the only one on the floor=C2=A0he might stop the grilling and be li=
ke =E2=80=9Cwait a minute, I told everyone to come back to the office, and =
you=E2=80=99re the only one here.=E2=80=9D And then he=E2=80=99ll go grill =
someone else about why the floor is empty.
More generally, anyone who has ever worked at a job has probably had the ex=
perience of (1) your boss tells you to do something, (2) you say =E2=80=9Cy=
es I will do that right away,=E2=80=9D and (3) you don=E2=80=99t do it and =
hope the boss forgets. But I feel like the very last boss I would try to pu=
ll this on is Jamie Dimon? He is famously up on all the details of his busi=
ness. Surely he=E2=80=99d notice that only the MDs are coming to work. I do=
n=E2=80=99t know.=C2=A0
Anyway the broader point of that story is that, unlike last year, we=E2=80=
=99re in=C2=A0a buyer=E2=80=99s market for investment banking talent:

=C2=A0The sense that it=E2=80=99s an employee=E2=80=99s job market where th=
e rank and file can set their own terms is fading. Ignoring edicts from the=
 C-suite is now a dangerous game. Few would dare.
At a small but growing number of firms, job cuts are back on the table. Thi=
s month, in a warning shot heard around the financial world, Goldman Sachs =
Group Inc. CEO David Solomon, another return-to-office stalwart, resumed th=
e firm=E2=80=99s practice of periodically culling underperformers to make w=
ay for new talent=E2=80=94an unsavory ritual that had been put on hold beca=
use of the pandemic. =E2=80=A6
The threat of job cuts takes center stage, but another concern is creeping =
up: Yearend bonuses are likely to plunge.
Incentive pay for dealmakers handling debt and equity offerings may tumble =
more than 45% this year, while advisers on mergers and acquisitions see the=
ir bonuses drop 25%, according to a closely watched report released in Augu=
st by compensation consultant Johnson Associates Inc.

This is the same story as the one in the previous section. Investment banki=
ng is a cyclical business, a leveraged bet on how the economy is feeling in=
 any given year. When the market is cheerful, you get paid huge fees for ar=
ranging big loans, you get a big bonus, and if your boss tells you that you=
 have to come into the office you can always quit and get another job. When=
 the market is bad, you lose money trying to place those loans, you get a s=
mall bonus, and you come to the office early each day so as not to give you=
r boss an excuse to fire you.

