<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Roaming Dimon</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Does <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbus=
iness.com/click/29137297.267530/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2F=
ydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDktMjIvd2FsbC1zdHJlZXQtY3VsbHMtc2lnbmFsLXdvcmtlci1zLWpvYi=
1tYXJrZXQtaXMtb3Zlcj9jbXBpZD1CQkQwOTIyMjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtY=
WlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjA5MjImdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1v=
bmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB317d508d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" items=
cope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  this work</a>?</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">JPMorgan Chase and Co. executives were in a bi=
nd. Amid a flurry of job-hopping on Wall Street last year, Chief Executive =
Officer Jamie Dimon had told the bank=E2=80=99s US staff it was time to ret=
urn to offices on a regular basis. But with Covid-19 cases climbing at the =
time, some managers were reluctant to take a hard line with staff who could=
 quit. A number of divisions were already wrestling with resignations and r=
acing to refill positions.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So an informal strategy emerged to shield the =
rank and file from the CEO=E2=80=99s dictate without antagonizing him, acco=
rding to people with direct knowledge of the matter, who asked not to be na=
med discussing internal practices.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyone who Dimon might possibly walk the halls=
 looking for, such as a managing director, needed to come into the office. =
They just couldn=E2=80=99t take the risk. Many others, though, were given l=
eeway to keep working from home discreetly. The recruiters were busy enough=
. (Joe Evangelisti, a spokesman for the bank, says assertions that such a s=
ystem existed are =E2=80=9Cfalse.=E2=80=9D)</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Well sure fine sometimes Jamie Dimon=C2=A0walk=
s the halls because he is looking for specific people; he wants to grill so=
me MD about a transaction and woe to her if he can=E2=80=99t find her. But=
=C2=A0<em>as he walks=C2=A0</em>=E2=80=94=C2=A0to find that MD, or to go to=
 lunch or whatever =E2=80=94=C2=A0he can look around, and if it=E2=80=99s a=
 ghost town he might notice. Like if he walks onto the trading floor to gri=
ll an MD about a trade and=C2=A0<em>she=E2=80=99s the only one on the floor=
</em>=C2=A0he might stop the grilling and be like =E2=80=9Cwait a minute, I=
 told everyone to come back to the office, and you=E2=80=99re the only one =
here.=E2=80=9D And then he=E2=80=99ll go grill someone else about why the f=
loor is empty.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">More generally, anyone who has ever worked at =
a job has probably had the experience of (1) your boss tells you to do some=
thing, (2) you say =E2=80=9Cyes I will do that right away,=E2=80=9D and (3)=
 you don=E2=80=99t do it and hope the boss forgets. But I feel like the ver=
y last boss I would try to pull this on is Jamie Dimon? He is famously up o=
n all the details of his business. Surely he=E2=80=99d notice that only the=
 MDs are coming to work. I don=E2=80=99t know.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway the broader point of that story is that=
, unlike last year, we=E2=80=99re in=C2=A0a buyer=E2=80=99s market for inve=
stment banking talent:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=C2=A0The sense that it=E2=80=99s an employee=
=E2=80=99s job market where the rank and file can set their own terms is fa=
ding. Ignoring edicts from the C-suite is now a dangerous game. Few would d=
are.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At a small but growing number of firms, job cu=
ts are back on the table. This month, in a warning shot heard around the fi=
nancial world, Goldman Sachs Group Inc. CEO David Solomon, another return-t=
o-office stalwart, resumed the firm=E2=80=99s practice of periodically cull=
ing underperformers to make way for new talent=E2=80=94an unsavory ritual t=
hat had been put on hold because of the pandemic. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The threat of job cuts takes center stage, but=
 another concern is creeping up: Yearend bonuses are likely to plunge.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Incentive pay for dealmakers handling debt and=
 equity offerings may tumble more than 45% this year, while advisers on mer=
gers and acquisitions see their bonuses drop 25%, according to a closely wa=
tched report released in August by compensation consultant Johnson Associat=
es Inc.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is the same story as the one in the previ=
ous section. Investment banking is a cyclical business, a leveraged bet on =
how the economy is feeling in any given year. When the market is cheerful, =
you get paid huge fees for arranging big loans, you get a big bonus, and if=
 your boss tells you that you have to come into the office you can always q=
uit and get another job. When the market is bad, you lose money trying to p=
lace those loans, you get a small bonus, and you come to the office early e=
ach day so as not to give your boss an excuse to fire you.</p>
