<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">PFOF</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There=E2=80=99s really nothing interesting abo=
ut payment for order flow. In the world of US retail stock brokers, <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29137297.267530/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDItMDUvcm9iaW5ob29k=
LWdhbWVzdG9wLXNhZ2EtcHJlc3N1cmVzLXBheW1lbnQtZm9yLW9yZGVyLWZsb3c_Y21waWQ9QkJ=
EMDkyMjIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZX=
ImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwOTIyJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319=
a23cBdf429944" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bl=
ank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; ba=
ckground-color: #ccc;">
the norm is</a> that the brokers route their customers=E2=80=99 orders to b=
uy or sell stock to a handful of big electronic market makers. These market=
 makers, knowing that they are trading only with retail investors, are will=
ing to give those retail investors a good deal: Those investors pay a narro=
wer spread (they can sell stock at higher prices and buy it at lower prices=
) than they would if their order went to the public stock exchange. On the =
public stock exchange, there are smart professional investors trading in hu=
ge size, and if you are a market maker trading with them, you will probably=
 regret many of your trades. If you are only trading with retail orders, yo=
u are less likely to regret your trades, so you can charge less.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is so true that the market makers can <a =
href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29137297.267530/aHR0c=
HM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDgtMjUvc29tZS1m=
cmVlLWJyb2tlcnMtYXJlLWNoZWFwZXItdGhhbi1vdGhlcnM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDkyMjIyX01PTkV=
ZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09Mj=
IwOTIyJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBaf991641" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;">  distinguish between retail brokerages</a>: Oversimplifying slightl=
y, customers with Interactive Brokers Pro accounts seem to pay wider spread=
s than customers of TD Ameritrade, presumably <em>because they are pros</em=
>, or at least more similar to professional investors (they make more infor=
med trades in larger size) than TD Ameritrade=E2=80=99s customers are.=C2=
=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This system has pluses and minuses. The main p=
lus is that the retail investors get better execution than institutional in=
vestors, which is nice for them. The main minus is that institutional inves=
tors get worse execution than they would if all the orders went to the publ=
ic stock exchange. (If market makers couldn=E2=80=99t segregate orders, the=
y=E2=80=99d probably end up charging retail investors more but institutiona=
l investors less =E2=80=94=C2=A0because they=E2=80=99d all pay the same spr=
ead.) You might think this is bad if =E2=80=94=C2=A0like me =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
you invest your money through mutual funds, which get worse execution. A wo=
rld where all orders were routed to the same public exchange might be a wor=
ld where mutual funds saved a bit of money on trade execution, at the expen=
se of Robinhood hobbyists.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">All this stuff matters at some level, though I=
 think people tend to overestimate how much it matters. But the payment for=
 order flow part? I don=E2=80=99t know, man. In addition to giving retail i=
nvestors tighter spreads, there is a norm that market makers pay the retail=
 brokers to trade with their customers=E2=80=99 orders. The retail brokers =
use this payment to subsidize commission-free trading for those customers. =
The customers are better off because they don=E2=80=99t pay commissions. Bu=
t this sort of looks unseemly: Are the brokers routing the orders to the ma=
rket makers who pay them the most? I mean, no, not really. Here is a good <=
a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29137297.267530/aHR=
0cHM6Ly9jb250ZW50LnNjaHdhYi5jb20vd2ViL3JldGFpbC9wdWJsaWMvYWJvdXQtc2Nod2FiL1=
NjaHdhYi0yMDIyLW9yZGVyLXJvdXRpbmctd2hpdGVwYXBlci5wZGY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a=
23cB86463e00" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bla=
nk" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;"> Charles Schwab paper</a> on =E2=80=9CU.S. Equity Mar=
ket Structure: Order Routing Practices, Considerations, and Opportunities=
=E2=80=9D:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Schwab does not route order flow t=
o the highest bidder (i.e., the market center that pays us the highest rate=
). Instead, we route orders to the market centers that provide our clients =
the best execution =E2=80=93 measured by price improvement amount, price im=
provement frequency, execution speed, fill rates, and enhanced liquidity. A=
s we detail below, we would advocate for the industry to require brokers to=
 receive the same level of payment for the same order flow across all marke=
t centers that they route to.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That seems to be the norm: Retail brokers have=
 a handful of market makers that they route to, they charge those market ma=
kers the same price schedule, and then they choose among them based on who =
provides the best prices to their customers. The story of =E2=80=9Cpayment =
for order flow is a bribe that electronic traders pay to brokers so they ca=
n rip off retail investors=E2=80=9D is obviously attractive =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
that=E2=80=99s what it sounds like! =E2=80=94=C2=A0but not especially true.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/29137297.267530/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL=
